","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Croft","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places, for example in Lincolnshire, Lancashire, Herefordshire, and North Yorkshire, all named with Old English <i>croft</i> ‘small arable enclosure (normally adjoining a house)’, or a topographic name for someone who lived by a croft, from Middle English <i>croft</i>.","English: possibly in some cases a variant of   Craft   2.","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . Compare   Kroft   and   Craft  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Craft","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>craft</i> ‘skillful, clever, learned’.","English: habitational name from Croft in Leicestershire. See also   Croft  .","Americanized form of German, Danish, Swedish, or Jewish   Kraft  . See also   Croft  ."]},{"name":"Crate","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): from Middle English <i>crate</i> ‘hurdle, basket’, or occasionally perhaps from <i>crete</i> ‘cradle’, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such articles. Alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Croft   1."]},{"name":"Crofts","meanings":["English: variant of   Croft  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Groft","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Croft  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":53,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William de Croft was born about 1402, in England. She had at least 1 son with William de Croft."},"et":{"about 1402–":"umbes 1402–Surnud","1393–1433":"1393–1433","1427–1509":"1427–1509","1402–Female":"1402–Surnud","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","about 1402":"umbes 1402","1509":"1509","1393":"1393","1427":"1427","Croft Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Croft, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1402–":"noin 1402–Kuollut","1393–1433":"1393–1433","1427–1509":"1427–1509","1402–Female":"1402–Kuollut","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","about 1402":